---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import MulchCalculator from '../components/MulchCalculator';
import FAQ from '../components/FAQ.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { getLangFromUrl, useTranslations } from '../i18n/utils';
import { Layers, Maximize2, DollarSign } from 'lucide-react';

const lang = getLangFromUrl(Astro.url);
const t = useTranslations(lang);
---

<Layout>
	<Nav lang={lang} />

	<main>
		<!-- Utility Section: Calculator at the top -->
		<section id="calculator" class="relative overflow-hidden pt-12 pb-24 px-6 border-b border-hairline bg-canvas">
			<!-- Background Decor - Subtler for utility focus -->
			<div class="absolute top-0 left-1/2 -translate-x-1/2 w-full max-w-7xl h-full -z-10 mesh-gradient opacity-30"></div>
			
			<div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto space-y-12">
				<div class="text-center space-y-4">
					<h1 class="display-lg text-ink">{t('calc.title')}</h1>
					<p class="body-md text-body max-w-2xl mx-auto">{t('calc.subtitle')}</p>
				</div>
				
				<div class="classical-card p-1 rounded-sm shadow-level-2 bg-canvas-soft border-hairline-strong">
					<MulchCalculator client:load lang={lang} />
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Theory & SEO Content Section: Professional Educational Content -->
		<section class="bg-canvas-soft py-24 px-6 border-t border-hairline">
			<div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto space-y-24">
				
				<!-- Main Theory Content -->
				<div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none 
					prose-headings:font-geist prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tighter
					prose-h2:text-display-lg prose-h2:mb-12 prose-h2:text-ink
					prose-h3:text-display-sm prose-h3:mt-0 prose-h3:mb-6 prose-h3:text-ink prose-h3:flex prose-h3:items-center prose-h3:gap-3
					prose-h3:before:content-[''] prose-h3:before:w-1 prose-h3:before:h-6 prose-h3:before:bg-primary prose-h3:before:rounded-full
					prose-p:text-body-md prose-p:text-body prose-p:leading-relaxed prose-p:mb-8
					prose-li:text-body-sm prose-li:text-body prose-li:mb-2
					prose-ul:list-disc prose-ul:pl-5 prose-ul:mb-8
					prose-strong:text-ink prose-strong:font-bold
					[&>div>section]:theory-section [&>div>section]:mb-12
				" set:html={t('seo.longContent')}>
				</div>

				<!-- Features Grid - Secondary Info -->
				<div id="features" class="space-y-16">
					<div class="text-center space-y-4">
						<h2 class="display-lg">{t('features.title')}</h2>
						<p class="body-md text-body">{t('features.description')}</p>
						<a href={lang === 'en' ? '/gravel-calculator' : `/${lang}/gravel-calculator`} class="inline-flex items-center justify-center classical-button h-10 px-5 mt-2">
							Try the Gravel Calculator
						</a>
					</div>

					<div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
						<div class="classical-card p-8 rounded-sm space-y-4">
							<div class="w-10 h-10 bg-cyan-soft rounded-sm border border-cyan-deep/20 flex items-center justify-center">
								<Layers className="w-5 h-5 text-cyan-deep" />
							</div>
							<h3 class="body-md-strong">{t('features.areaTitle')}</h3>
							<p class="body-sm text-body">{t('features.areaText')}</p>
						</div>
						<div class="classical-card p-8 rounded-sm space-y-4">
							<div class="w-10 h-10 bg-violet-soft rounded-sm border border-violet-deep/20 flex items-center justify-center">
								<Maximize2 className="w-5 h-5 text-violet-deep" />
							</div>
							<h3 class="body-md-strong">{t('features.shapesTitle')}</h3>
							<p class="body-sm text-body">{t('features.shapesText')}</p>
						</div>
						<div class="classical-card p-8 rounded-sm space-y-4">
							<div class="w-10 h-10 bg-warning-soft rounded-sm border border-warning-deep/20 flex items-center justify-center">
								<DollarSign className="w-5 h-5 text-warning-deep" />
							</div>
							<h3 class="body-md-strong">{t('features.costTitle')}</h3>
							<p class="body-sm text-body">{t('features.costText')}</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="bg-canvas px-6 py-20 border-t border-hairline">
			<div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose prose-neutral max-w-none
				prose-headings:font-geist prose-headings:font-semibold prose-headings:tracking-tighter
				prose-h2:text-display-md prose-h2:text-ink
				prose-h3:text-display-sm prose-h3:text-ink
				prose-p:text-body-md prose-p:text-body prose-p:leading-relaxed
				prose-li:text-body-sm prose-li:text-body
				prose-strong:text-ink">
				<h2>Landscape Material Calculators Built for Real Projects</h2>
				<p>
					Mulchcalculator1.com is designed to help homeowners, landscapers, and contractors estimate outdoor materials with confidence before they buy. The main mulch calculator focuses on garden beds, tree rings, playground areas, and decorative landscape coverage, while our new <a href={lang === 'en' ? '/gravel-calculator' : `/${lang}/gravel-calculator`}>gravel calculator</a> helps plan driveways, paths, patios, paver bases, and stone projects. Both tools are built around practical job-site math: measure the area, choose a depth, compare bulk and bagged material, and order with less waste.
				</p>
				<p>
					A good calculator should do more than display one number. Real landscape projects often require several buying formats. Mulch is commonly sold by cubic yard or bag, while gravel can be sold by cubic yard, ton, or bag depending on the supplier. That is why the gravel calculator includes high-value outputs for cubic yards, tons, metric tonnes, cubic feet, cubic meters, and bag count. If you are searching for a <strong>gravel calculator yards</strong> tool, a <strong>driveway gravel calculator</strong>, or a <strong>paver gravel calculator</strong>, the dedicated gravel page gives you a faster way to compare all of those ordering units in one place.
				</p>
				<h3>Why accurate material estimates matter</h3>
				<p>
					Buying too little material can delay a project, create color mismatch between separate deliveries, and add extra delivery fees. Buying too much can leave piles of unused mulch, pea gravel, or crushed stone that are difficult to store or remove. Accurate estimates also help with budgeting because they let you compare bulk delivery against retail bags before you commit. For small garden beds, bags may be convenient. For a long driveway, bulk gravel is usually more efficient. The calculator workflow makes those tradeoffs clear on desktop and mobile devices.
				</p>
				<p>
					Depth is especially important. A thin mulch layer may not suppress weeds or retain moisture effectively, while an overly deep layer can harm plants. Gravel projects have the same issue: a decorative path may only need a shallow layer, but a driveway usually needs more depth and stronger base material. The <strong>gravel calculator for driveway</strong> page accounts for depth, density, and compaction allowance so your estimate better reflects real installation conditions. It can also be used as a <strong>pea gravel calculator</strong> for decorative areas or a <strong>crushed gravel calculator</strong> for compacted base projects.
				</p>
				<h3>Built for speed, clarity, and mobile use</h3>
				<p>
					Many calculator websites are cluttered with slow layouts, confusing forms, and hard-to-read results. This website is intentionally cleaner. The calculators load quickly, keep the most important inputs near the top, and display results in clear cards that are easy to read on a phone at a job site or store aisle. You can switch between imperial and metric units, use common shapes such as rectangles, circles, and triangles, and adjust pricing assumptions to match your local supplier.
				</p>
				<p>
					For best results, measure each project section separately and add them together. Include a small waste factor for irregular edges, settling, compaction, and measurement errors. Then confirm the final order with your local material supplier, especially for driveway gravel, crushed stone, or paver base where soil conditions and traffic load can change the required depth. These calculators are built to give you a reliable planning estimate, reduce guesswork, and make it easier to order the right amount of material the first time.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<FAQ lang={lang} />
	</main>

	<Footer lang={lang} />
</Layout>
